            <entry xml:id="entry_æng0yr" xml:lang="os">
                <form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma"><orth>æng˳yr</orth></form>
                <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>ænguræ</orth></form>
                <sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>удочка</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>fishing rod</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>рыболовный крюк</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>angle</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense></sense>
                <abv:exampleGrp>
                    <abv:example>
                        <quote>acū denǵyzmæ, bappar æng˳yr æmæ fyccag cy kæsagyl fæxæst waj,
                            rajs</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>пойди на море, брось уду и первую рыбу, которая попадется, возьми</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>go thou to the sea, and cast an hook, and take up the fish that first
                                cometh up</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Матфей"/><biblScope>17
                            27</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                </abv:exampleGrp>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Содержит тот же корень, что <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_æng0ylʒ"/> ‘палец’ (--→ „крючок“, „крючкообразный предмет“).
                    Ближайшие по форме и значению соответствия — <mentioned xml:lang="goh"><lang/>
                        <w>angul</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/>
                        <w>Angel</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="en"><lang/>
                        <w>angle</w>
                        <gloss><q>удочка</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>άγκυρα</w>
                        <gloss><q>якорь</q></gloss></mentioned>. Ср. также <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/>
                        <w>anka-</w>
                        <gloss><q>крюк</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>aka-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><w>anku-</w></mentioned>
                    (в %iankupəsəmna%i-), <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>ὂγκος</w>
                        <gloss><q>крюк</q></gloss></mentioned>, ‘крючок’, %iάγκύλος%i ‘изогнутый’,
                        <mentioned xml:lang="la"><lang/>
                        <w>uncus</w>
                        <gloss><q>крючок</q></gloss></mentioned> и др. Индоевропейские формы
                    предполагают две исходные разновидности корня, *%iank%i- и *%iang%i-, которые в
                    осетинском должны были совпасть (ср. <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Walde—Pok."/><biblScope>I 60 сл.</biblScope></bibl>). Ср.
                        <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æng0ylʒ"/> ‘палец’.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Brugmann"/><biblScope> B. II, T. I, стр.
                            367—368</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"/><biblScope>II 57,
                    67</biblScope></bibl>.%n</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">It has the same root as in <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_æng0ylʒ"/> ‘finger’ (→ “hook”, “a hook-like item”). The
                    closest corresponding forms by meaning and form are <mentioned xml:lang="goh"><lang/>
                        <w>angul</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/>
                        <w>Angel</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="en"><lang/>
                        <w>angle</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>άγκυρα</w>
                        <gloss><q>anchor</q></gloss></mentioned>. Compare also <mentioned
                        xml:lang="sa"><lang/>
                        <w>anka-</w>
                        <gloss><q>hook</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>aka-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><w>anku-</w></mentioned>
                    (in %iankupəsəmna-%i), <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>ὂγκος</w>
                        <gloss><q>hook, fish-hook</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"
                            ><w>άγκύλος</w>
                        <gloss><q>curved</q></gloss></mentioned> , <mentioned xml:lang="la"><lang/>
                        <w>uncus</w>
                        <gloss><q>hook</q></gloss></mentioned> etc. Indo-European forms suppose to
                    have two initial variants of the root, *%iank%i- and *%iang%i-, which must have
                    coincided (compare <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Walde—Pok."/><biblScope>I
                            60%bсл.%b</biblScope></bibl>). Compare <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_æng0ylʒ"/> ‘finger’.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Brugmann"/><biblScope>B. II, T. I,
                        pp.367—368</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"/><biblScope>II 57,
                    67</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
            </entry>
